3","about 1294":"omkring 1294","1232":"1232","1285":"1285","1230":"1230","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","11 November 1306":"11. november 1306","1306":"1306","Flint, Flintshire, Wales":"Flint, Flintshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Flint,Wales":"Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1260–11 November 1306":"1260–11 november 1306","1260–1306":"1260–1306","1230–Female":"1230–Overleden","1294–Female":"1294–Overleden","1230–Male":"1230–Overleden","1232–1285":"1232–1285","ABT 1293":"circa 1293","about 1294":"circa 1294","1232":"1232","1285":"1285","1230":"1230","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","11 November 1306":"11 november 1306","1306":"1306","Flint, Flintshire, Wales":"Flint, Flintshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Flint,Wales":"Flintshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1260–11 November 1306":"1260–11 November 1306","1260–1306":"1260–1306","1230–Female":"1230–Deceased","1294–Female":"1294–Deceased","1230–Male":"1230–Deceased","1232–1285":"1232–1285","ABT 1293":"about 1293","about 1294":"about 1294","1232":"1232","1285":"1285","1230":"1230","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","11 November 1306":"11 November 1306","1306":"1306","Flint, Flintshire, Wales":"Flint, Flintshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Flint,Wales":"Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Madog","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French Canadian: variant of   Madore  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Madore","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Eusebe, Fernand, Lucien, Normand, Adhemar, Adrien, Donat, Elzear, Francois, Gaetan, Gilles.","French Canadian: from a French shortened form of the Spanish personal name <i>Amador</i>, from Latin <i>Amator</i> (from <i>amator</i> ‘lover’), a Christian saint's name. Compare   Mador  .","In some cases possibly also Breton (<b>Madoré</b>): nickname meaning literally ‘good help’, from Old Breton <i>mat</i> ‘good’ and <i>uuoret</i> ‘help’."]}]},{"name":"Madog","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name, possibly having the sense ‘fortunate’ or alternatively from Celtic <i>aodh</i> ‘fire’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Fychan","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Welsh: A Welsh name of great antiquity, from vyckan, little, small; i.e. small in stature. Compare the surname Bychan and the Armoric Le Bihan."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Madog Fychan ap Madog Crypl was born in 1260, in Flint, Flintshire, Wales, his father, Madoc Crypl ap Gruffydd Vychan, was 30 and his mother, Margaret verch Rhys Vychan, was 28. He married Gwladus verch Gruffydd about 1293, in Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 11 November 1306, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1260–11 November 1306":"1260–11. november 1306","1260–1306":"1260–1306","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1294–Female":"1294–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1232–1285":"1232–1285","ABT 1293":"umbes 1293","about 1294":"umbes 1294","1232":"1232","1285":"1285","1230":"1230","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","11 November 1306":"11. november 1306","1306":"1306","Flint, Flintshire, Wales":"Flint, Flintshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Flint,Wales":"Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1260–11 November 1306":"1260–11. marraskuuta 1306","1260–1306":"1260–1306","1230–Female":"1230–Kuollut","1294–Female":"1294–Kuollut","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1232–1285":"1232–1285","ABT 1293":"noin 1293","about 1294":"noin 1294","1232":"1232","1285":"1285","1230":"1230","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","11 November 1306":"11. marraskuuta 1306","1306":"1306","Flint, Flintshire, Wales":"Flint, Flintshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Flint,Wales":"Flintshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1260–11 November 1306":"1260–11 novembre 1306","1260–1306":"1260–1306","1230–Female":"1230–Décédée","1294–Female":"1294–Décédée","1230–Male":"1230–Décédé","1232–1285":"1232–1285","A